==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{term/t|la|acerbātus}}, perfect passive participle of {{term/t|la|acerbō||make bitter}}, from {{term|acerbus||bitter|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈasəbeɪt/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈæsəɹˌbeɪt/}}, ASS-uhr-bait

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# {{context|rare|lang=en}} [[embittered|Embittered]]; having a [[sour]] [[disposition]] or nature.

===Verb===
{{en-verb|acerbat|es}}

# To [[exasperate]]; to [[irritate]]. 
#* '''1869''', [[w:Anthony Trollope|Anthony Trollope]], ''Phineas Finn'', ch. 51:
#*: Lady Laura had triumphed; but she had no desire to '''acerbate''' her husband by any unpalatable allusion to her victory.
# To make [[bitter]] or sour.

